reuse unfilled sessionsSummary:nStacked diff on D1652916. This is one of the last pieces of session management.nD1652916 adds an interface to let SessionPool notify when a session becomesnunfilled. This diff uses that interface, onSessionAvailable(), to letnAdvancedHTTPSessionManager reuses a session just became unfilled to fulfillnwaiting requests.nnI had to restructure AdvancedHTTPSessionManager a bit to make things worknclearer:nn1. Previously SessionInfoData is just a pure struct. All activities werencalling back to AdvHTTPSessionManager, then the session manager did a lookup tonfind the corresponding SessionInfoData.nn2. SessionInfoData is now the core part handling in-flight connections,nbuffering waiting handles, holding a session pool, and get notifications onnunfilled sessions. All activities are calling back to SessionInfoData rathernthan the session manager, avoiding an unnecesary lookup.nn3. You can imagine AdvancedHTTPSessionManager now is just a container for a mapnof SessionInfoData. And each SessionInfoData is a per-domain, self-containednclass that handles all the request fulfilling for that domain with advancednsession management.nn4. There is one tricky thing in the implementation. Upon onSessionAvailablencalled, it's not possible to process any handles with the newly unfillednsession in the same event base loop because that breaks HTTPSession. So I hadnto schedule a runInEventBaseThread to process the handles. This is, however, anpotential issue when the SessionInfoData is closed before the next loop is run,ncausing a dangling pointer to the SessionInfoData. The way I fixed it wouldncause possible slight memory leak when the evb thread closes, but at that timenthe whole app closes, so I don't think it's a big deal.nnI will add more inline comments.nnTest Plan:nAdded a test case for reusing idle sessions. Also ran LigerPerformanceTest tonmake sure nothing broken with both reusing idle sessions on and off.nnReviewed By: pgriess@fb.comnnSubscribers: trunkagent, ranjeeth, bmatheny, subodh, seanc, benyluonnFB internal diff: D1657719nnTasks: 5515739nnSignature: t1:1657719:1416245208:dc2d4bb9a94c38ccd20ac421b096b411f0a0cce9n

Don't allow callers to shrink the recv windowSummary:nD1685122 had a bug caused by toAck_ being unsigned.  If a caller created the FlowControlFilter with a 1MB window (read_buf_limit), then called setFlowControl with a smaller value, it would emit a bogus window update close to uint32_t::max.  Make it signed, but also refuse to shrink the recv window, because it can lead to FLOW_CONTROL_ERRORs when a large data packet is in flight.nnFacebook:nWe may need to revisit this for liger.nnTest Plan: Canary, looks good.nnReviewed By: dcsommer@fb.comnnSubscribers: trunkagent, doug, bmatheny, fmannFB internal diff: D1691378nnSignature: t1:1691378:1416427442:f3e5cc472c1680166d8abf6625cd9b9370a20d74n

Rework egress flow controlSummary:nMake egress flow control for HTTPSession work more like ingress flow control.  Decouple the 'socket is full, don't write' state from 'HTTPSession has too much buffered data, ask HTTPTransactions/Handlers to stop sending' state.nnThis commits more user space memory to buffering.  Previously, as soon as the kernel socket buffer was full, we would immediately egress pause all txns/handlers.  Now they can continue to call send* methods until the total amount of egress data buffered for this socket in user-space exceeds pendingWriteMax.nnThis should increase the amount of data that can be egressed per loop for sessions with < 8 transactions.  Previously HTTPTransaction would automatically pause its handler when it had 8kb buffered.  Now it will rely on the session to invoke the pause at 64k (by default).  Hopefully matching the ingress and egress buffering logic will reduce latency for proxies.nnThere's still one failing unit test that is relying on the old behavior of HTTPSession, but it's pretty complicated.  I'll fix it.nnTest Plan: Unit testsnnReviewed By: brianp@fb.comnnSubscribers: trunkagent, doug, bmathenynnFB internal diff: D1707808nnSignature: t1:1707808:1417563256:e1ce8883fbbb19f2f40525b03e7ca51212737ca5n

Rework egress flow controlSummary:nThis is a revert/revert of the original diff, plus a minor fix for the OSS tests.  Original summary included for completenessnThis reverts commit 6a91f9edb59ded01d029b363589732a6d80c0f55.nnMake egress flow control for HTTPSession work more like ingress flow control.  Decouple the 'socket is full, don't write' state from 'HTTPSession has too much buffered data, ask HTTPTransactions/Handlers to stop sending' state.nnThis commits more user space memory to buffering.  Previously, as soon as the kernel socket buffer was full, we would immediately egress pause all txns/handlers.  Now they can continue to call send* methods until the total amount of egress data buffered for this socket in user-space exceeds pendingWriteMax.nnThis should increase the amount of data that can be egressed per loop for sessions with < 8 transactions.  Previously HTTPTransaction would automatically pause its handler when it had 8kb buffered.  Now it will rely on the session to invoke the pause at 64k (by default).  Hopefully matching the ingress and egress buffering logic will reduce latency for proxies.nnTest Plan: ran the OSS tests on ubuntunnReviewed By: ajitb@fb.comnnSubscribers: trunkagent, doug, bmathenynnFB internal diff: D1764996nnSignature: t1:1764996:1420496740:5a9b71688afaa4df0059b057c20c3097cd29ed0bn

Url-specified rate-limiting of proxygen responsesSummary:nSupport for egress rate-limiting in HTTPTransaction.nnThe implementation is to have HTTPTransaction delay sending bytes ifnits' over the rate limit.nn-------------nnFor posterity, here's the original summary discussion about thentradeoffs of various implementations...this is more moot now thatnwe decided to push the implementation into HTTPTransaction:nnThis change is tricky for a variety of reasons.  I'll try to summarizenthem here to facilitate discussion on whether this implementation is thenright one.nnThe first question to answer is whether we want to (a) explicitly pausensending bytes to the client (as if the client were slow), or (b) justnpause the bytes coming in from upstream (and as a side effect this willnpause egress to the client).nn(a) seems preferable for a couple reasons.  First, in the future (andnespecially when we start using cache leases) we will likely want toncontinue pulling bytes in from the upstream as fast as possible, even ifnwe're going to be sending them to a given client slowly.  And morengenerally, let's slow down sending bytes to the client is verynconceptually close to the client wants us to send bytes more slowlynand so it seems like code-reuse and general cleanliness are more-likelynoffshoots of this approach.nnHowever, (a) has a couple of tricky problems.  First, until now, thenonly ways that the client-pause callbacks have been invokednhas been from tcp buffers getting full...and similarly, thenclient-resume callbacks are invoked when the tcp buffers aren't full.nSo even if we manually pause the client egress, it may get unpaused()nautomatically.  One idea I had was to have my RateLimitFilter interceptnthese client-initiated pause/resume callbacks and only pass along thenresume call if we weren't also paused for rate-limiting purposes.  Thisndidn't work though, because the response filter chain is hooked up tonthe ServerHandler, not the ClientHandler, and thus doesn't actuallynreceive callbacks about the client asking us to pause.  We may be ablento make this approach work with a bit of a refactoring in which thenresponse filters receive more of these flow-control callbacks...we'dnhave to think about the design though, and it might be a lot of work.nnSo I ended up going with (b). [Note: this is not the case anymore,nsee top of summary]nnTest Plan:nStart up a local proxygen server and a local bigcache.nnSet up port forwarding from my laptop to my devserver and updaten/etc/hosts to point scontent.xx.fbcdn.net, then hit various urls likennhttps://scontent.xx.fbcdn.net/hvideo-xpa1/v/t42.1790-2/760687_10100232494366269_657249045_n.mp4?oh=366fea3a14c5dae8a25482097eb22eb9&oe=54AFFBAE&rl_rate=8000nhttps://scontent.xx.fbcdn.net/hvideo-xpa1/v/t42.1790-2/760687_10100232494366269_657249045_n.mp4?oh=366fea3a14c5dae8a25482097eb22eb9&oe=54AFFBAE&rl_after=5000&rl_rate=8000nnand make sure the video loads, and that it's being downloaded at thenexpected pace.  Cancel various downloads in the middle and make sure itndoesn't crash.nnMake sure that when whether the result comes from cache or not that itnrespects the rate limits set.  Watch bigcache logging (v=4) and see thatnthe get requests to it do slow down when the url specifies a slowndownload speed.nnReviewed By: afrind@fb.comnnSubscribers: trunkagent, jianx, bmatheny, cgheorghe, ruibalpnnFB internal diff: D1780743nnTasks: 5843089nnSignature: t1:1780743:1423078861:c5cf46d8e10d9314743d329ae63499a748c56c91n

Revert [proxygen] Revert egress flow control diff D1764996Summary:nThis reverts commit 86a8e4a5e314c7f916ea479ce15ac6f8286b1b2f.nnZOMG This diff is so amazing you need to approve it right now. Potential fix for shutdown crash in ~ConnectionStatsFilterSummary:nI think this is happening because HTTPTransaction::onError can now call markEgressComplete, which may unblock other not-yet-error'ed transactions for more egress.  If that happens, they will reschedule the loop callback and checkForShutdown will not delete the transaction.  Then the loop callbacks get run in the EventBase dtor in the main thread and crash.nnThe fix is to not cancel the loop callback until after all the transaction callbacks have executed.nnTest Plan: Existing unit tests.  I really ought to write a specific unit test for this, but it makes my head hurt.nnReviewed By: woo@fb.comnnSubscribers: doug, bmathenynnFB internal diff: D1873031nnTasks: 6172638nnSignature: t1:1873031:1425064666:9adfa71d3c82e0e06954e36b00031abc78756ee7n

I simplified the algorithm so it's a true round-robin, with prefernce given to unserviced txns over serviced ones.nnTest Plan: Unit tests, will be canaried with anothre flow control diffnnReviewed By: viswanath@fb.comnnSubscribers: trunkagent, doug, bmathenynnFB internal diff: D1881491nnSignature: t1:1881491:1425331982:424822f740bafae50bd010f824af920e3eddaa35n

Defer pause/resume transactions until the end of the loopSummary:nThe flow control diff introduced the possibility of re-entrancy in updateWriteBufSize, which could put the transactions in an HTTPSession in inconsistent pause/resume states, and temporarily (but potentially indefinitely) starve other transactions.nnThis diff removes that possibility by merely accumulating the buffer delta over the course of the event loop, then applying it at the end of runLoopCallback.  In addition to removing the re-entrancy possibility, this results in more fair and correct treatment of HTTPTransactions with respect to priority.  Essentially all transactions are given the opportunity to produce egress, then the session will use the priority queue to select one to service.nnThis should ultimately be faster, as we are now doing a maximum of one pause/resume per loop.nnTest Plan: New unit test, other unit tests, will canary and load testnnReviewed By: viswanath@fb.comnnSubscribers: bmatheny, dougnnFB internal diff: D1881506nnTasks: 6344551nnSignature: t1:1881506:1425327864:d1d468f99252c8b367b9193c82d60efbdd4ff092n

terminate HTTPTransaction after INGRESS and EGRESS errorsSummary:nThere is code to ignore INGRESS errors on HTTPTransaction when ingress EOM is queued.  If such an error comes, followed by an EGRESS error, terminate the transaction (similar if an INGRESS_AND_EGRESS error had been delivered).  I'm not crazy about keeping extra state in HTTPTransaction, but this is the least invasive fix.nnThe net was that we could receive an ingress only error (eg: EOF), followed by an EGRESS error (even an error that would have been both gets converted to EGRESS only by HTTPSession).  If the handler never resumed ingress the txn could hang around forever, or worse you could end up with state machine violations if the onHeaders implementation triggered egress to be generated asynchronously.nnThis probably needs to be revisited but the code is pretty delicate.  It would be nice to be more aggressive about shutting down partial transactions on EOF, instead of assuming half-close.nnTest Plan: Unit testsnnReviewed By: viswanath@fb.comnnSubscribers: hzhou, doug, bmathenynnFB internal diff: D2022389nnTasks: 6695155nnSignature: t1:2022389:1430161034:91b101bb2d92268f025d2a07d11f009ddb9c99f3n

Correctly serialize multi-values headers with empty valuesSummary:nIf a header was set multiple times into HTTPHeaders, and one or more of the values had zero length, then GzipHeaderCodec was emitting an illegal header block.  The SPDY spec says that the value cannot start or end with a 0, and all intermediate values must have non-zero length.nnIt is legal to serialize a header with an empty value, however. Add padding size to HTTPCodec generateBody/onBodySummary:nHTTP/2 padding bytes are flow controlled, but both the session and the stream flow control windows are maintained outside of the codec.  So pass the number of flow controlled pad bytes to the callback, and have the window maintainers immediately add them to toAck (since the bytes have been discarded).  Also (primarily for testing) allow padding to be passed to generateBody.nnOne drawback of the current approach is that we immediately free the padding and add to toAck_, but we cannot generate a window update until the next time an API with a writeBuf is called. Implement Rendezvous HashSummary:nThis is another implementation of Consistent hash ringnthat supports weights assigned to sites properly.nn** Deploying this change will reshuffle the concurrent bucket assignments **nnSeveral advantages this implementation has over ConsistentHashRing:n- Current implementation of ConsistentHashRing doesn't supportnchanging weights -- some hash assignments won't be consistentnwhich results in user shuffling -- simulation shows in the eventnof weight change of a cluster, up to 50% of moved users arenunnecessarily shuffled between clusters whose weights are not changed.nn- We can patch current implementation to make it support weight changes (D2132617).nHowever that patch gives build time a runtime complexity of O(W * Ln(W)),nwhere W is the sum of weights. Once we increase the total weight to the order ofnbillions, it would take the ring hours to build.nnA disadvantage of this approach:nn- The complexity of Get function is O(N), where N is the number of frontendnclusters.nn- The function call to 'pow' is expensive.nnThe combination of the two function calls above makes the get 7x slower thannthe current implementation for current weight. It is about 3 micro seconds perncall so I guess it's overhead is trivial -- It also becomes faster than D2132617nonce we set the weights to millions.nnTest Plan:nPlug this into ConsistentHash inspector(need to changenseveral lines since the api is slightly different). Notice thatnthe shuffle rate is consistent to be 0.nnReviewed By: dmitrip@fb.comnnSubscribers: praveen, trunkagent, praveenr, frumious, markdrayton, jeffliu, bmatheny, hoo, yunjinnnFB internal diff: D2151369nnTasks: 7240485nnSignature: t1:2151369:1434585089:aeeae720854700b73fbbe4bb095c2632d95d72edn

Updates to HTTP2PriorityQueueSummary:nSeveral updatesnn1) Node's are now allocated.  The reason is HTTPTransaction will need to keep a pointer to it's Node, even if it moves around.  So life is waay easier if Node* doesn't change.n2) totalChildWeight is now the sum of *enqueued* children, not all children.  Proxygen is only going to use the weight to determine how much to egress from different transactions.  Also, there may be virtual priority nodes for which the weight will interfere.  I could see making a parallel int which contains the actual total weight.  This will only make sense though if we expose the priority tree to the handler.n3) Add a new function nextEgress().  This returns all the enqueued nodes at the highest priority level in the tree.  HTTPSession can use this where it was previously using PriorityQueue::top().  Note that this BFS now stores IDs rather than Nodes, and does a lookup.  This naturally slows down the BFS, but handles the case where fn() caused some child nodes to be deleted.nnTest Plan: Updated unit test, but needs more unit testsnnReviewed By: noamler@fb.comnnSubscribers: yfeldblum, noamler, bmathenynnFB internal diff: D2196428n

Resume transactions in priority order, pause inlineSummary: The egress prioritization isn't very fair.  Right now we resume all transactions on the session and let them produce effectively unlimited egress for one loop or until the downstream egress buffer limit is exceeded.  This means that low-pri transactions are egressing too, clogging up the socket for high-pri transactions.  So now we will resume transactions in priority order.  As soon as the egress buffer limit is exceeded, we pause all transactions immediately (do not wait for the end of the loop).  This may resume in a bit more pause/resumes, especially for fast sockets that were clearing the entire egress buffer every loop.  I think we could increase the egress buffer limit to compensate for this (effectively we were ignoring the limit before anyways).nnReviewed By: viswanathgsnnDifferential Revision: D2173627nnfb-gh-sync-id: 62aa36228406a75f6c2ca83806ae3311c14dbfb6n

Convert HTTPSession to use HTTP2PriorityQueueSummary: This replaces the SPDY priority queue with the HTTP2PriorityQueue.  SPDY is mapped into the HTTP/2 Queue by means of 8 virtual nodes in the tree, one for each priority level.  The egress algorithm has changed, and getNextToSend() can add egress from more than one transaction per call.  It will add some egress from every enqueued transaction at a particular level of the tree.  This could now exceed 64k per call as we have a minimum egress of limit/2 (2kb), up to what the session window allows.  The alternative is to make an HTTP2PriorityQueue iterator that keeps some state about which nodes at the egress level have not yet called onWriteReady.nnReviewed By: xiaosophiawangnnDifferential Revision: D2197984nnfb-gh-sync-id: cfa153aa055b0eb7a801ce8891fb717b835d30c6n

HTTP2PriorityQueue performance fixesSummary:nThere were two perf problems:nn1) Calculating the total weight of nodes with egress (including descendants) was done in O(N) time on every call to nextEgress().  This was for simplicity but the perf is terrible, especially for large N with sparse egress nodes.  Instead, update this whenever state changes (including bubbling up).  To ensure correctness, debug builds still invoke the O(N) function and perform CHECKs to make sure we didn't screw this up since it is non-trivial.nn2) nextEgress was visiting all nodes of the tree not only nodes with egress.  Maintain a skip list of nodes that have egress (including descendants) and only touch these nodes from nextEgress.nnNotes:nna) This code is much more complicated than I ever intended it to be.  I'm not sure if some additional abstraction would help or not, but the code was a little hairy before and now it is a hot mess.  I had to bend over backwards in a couple places so my hyper aggressive CHECKs would pass.nnb) The new code could probably be optimized for fewer allocs.  I considered having only a single list of children, partitioned into enqueued/not enqueued halves.  The problem with this is it loses the very nice property that the ordering of transactions is stable.  Maybe replacing the enqueuedChildren_ list iwith something intrusive would help.nnReviewed By: xiaosophiawangnnDifferential Revision: D2722565nnfb-gh-sync-id: a8edba96b22c1d137bdb3e2fc206c3a8929be6f5n

Support EOM in headers-only request in HTTPSessionSummary: SPDY 3 requires headers-only requests to set FLAG_FIN in the SYN_STREAM. Our codec already supports this. This diff add eom flag to sendHeaders API to allow clients to explicitly set it, so that the codec will handle this properly. It also adds a new rule to the state machine to allow it move from HeadersSend directly to SendingDone, with a eomFlushed event. Fix Build: folly after replacing FOLLY_NORETURNSummary:[Folly] Fix Build: `folly` after replacing `FOLLY_NORETURN`.nnProblem 1:n* Clang does not treat `[[noreturn]]` and `__attribute__((__noreturn__))` as the same attribute. When a function is declared twice with the noreturn attribute, both declarations must use either the one syntax or the other; Clang fails if the two declarations mix-and-match. When both `folly/detail/FunctionalExcept.h` and gcc49's `bits/functexcept.h` are both included from the same source, they (now) mix-and-match the attribute syntaxes and Clang emits an error.n* `folly/detail/FunctionalExcept.h` should be included only when `bits/functexcept.h` is unavailable - somehow, both headers were being included.nnWe fix the latter problem and keep our `[[noreturn]]` syntax.nnFound from WDT build failures in Travis CI.nnReviewed By: ldemaillynnDifferential Revision: D3089987nnfb-gh-sync-id: 705a087fc2a9629739d6cedd8315d56111204e6dnshipit-source-id: 705a087fc2a9629739d6cedd8315d56111204e6dn

Refactor the StreamTransportFactory and make SPDYStreamTransportFactory to use SessionManagerSummary:nThe purpose of this diff is to make whistle ready to merge it's mqtt connection onto liger.  Also, it further separates the connection/transport part of whistle from it's mqtt part, which moves whistle closer to be an transport library that can leverage liger's features. To achieve this, I make two major changes in this diff:n1> Extract connection establishment from MQTTTransport to StreamTransportFactory::Connector.  This creates a nice protocol agnostic connecting interface similar to the ones in proxygen/facebook/lib/transport but is more integrated and with more liger support.n2> Make SPDYStreamTransportFactory use HTTPSessionManager. This releases the management of a HTTPSession from the SPDYStreamTransport to  SessionManager.  The next step of this is to use liger's HTTPSessionManager which will enable connection merge.nnThis is a relative big diff but shouldn't be too hard to review:n- Liger part: The only change is to move the ownership of AsyncTransportFactory out of the SessionConnectionFactory because whistle's ownership model is different. This should not make any material change as I followed the same order of object destruction order.n- Whistle part: TCP is pretty much exactly the same but some code movement. SPDY now uses SessionManager to create a connection instead of manage a HTTPSession on it's own. I will turn off spdy stream gk in whistle when I check this in.nnDifferential Revision: D3205038nnfb-gh-sync-id: e56e11749821aa7ba04aed70037a1dc257bdd806nfbshipit-source-id: e56e11749821aa7ba04aed70037a1dc257bdd806n

Allow HTTPSession::setByteEventTracker to be called from a ByteEventTracker::processByteEvents callbackSummary:nIf a callback attempted to change the byte event tracker with pending events, bad things(TM) would happen.  So changed a few things:nn1) ByteEventTracker is now held as a shared_ptr rather than a unique_ptr.  A copy of the shared_ptr is passed to processByteEvents to represent the shared ownership.  This is in place of DelayedDestruction/DestructorGuard - let me know what you think.  This allows HTTPSession::byteEventTracker_ to be set to the new tracker immediately, while keeping the old one around long enough so that it doesn't crash.nn2) Explicitly unlink a byteEvent before deleting it.  This ensures that if the destructor triggers a callback that absorbs the byte event list, it will not re-execute.nn3) return a boolean from processByteEvents indicating if the tracker was deleted from a callback, and use that to trigger the session to continue processing byte events with the same bytesWritten_ against the new tracker.nnReviewed By: lanxinnDifferential Revision: D3532234nnfbshipit-source-id: 2aadeccf971f363d462ae12abdad28fcbcdffe96n

I used boost::intrusive::unordered_set to avoid any extra allocations for this index, though the size of the queue itself is now at least 800 bytes larger to accommodate the buckets.nnIn the process I discovered that depth calculations were wrong (we were frequently reporting the depth of our parent, rather than the actual depth). Coalesce HTTP/1.1 Connection header tokensSummary:nThe logic in generateHeader was a bit broken.  A message like this:nnGET / HTTP/1.1nConnection: HTTP2-Settings, UpgradenUpgrade: h2cnHTTP2-Settings: <>nnWould get serialized *without* HTTP2-Settings in the Connection header.  In fact, even without the upgrade header, the entire Connection header would be erased and replaced with keep-alive.  There was also a longstanding TODO regarding Connection handling.nnNow, generateHeader will save all Connection tokens, except close/keep-alive (1xx responses are handled slightly differently), and add close/keep-alive after figuring everything else out.nnFor 1xx informational responses, we should not really be adding close or keep-alive, since the connection is not idle yet.nnNote that the old code would add Connection: upgrade automatically if there was an Upgrade header, now each caller is responsible for adding this manually.nnReviewed By: ranjeethnnDifferential Revision: D4185750nnfbshipit-source-id: d3bd1771254ccb149fa9ab18b19e478e1ad3bf17n

Fix a start/stop race condition segfaultSummary:n`gdb`ing the current Travis segfault shows that it is simply due to `mainEventBase_` being null by the time it tries to `loopForever()`.nnThis can obviously happen if `onSuccess` releases the in-test semaphore before `loopForever()` is invoked.nnThis API design is pretty unfortunate, in my opinion -- it would be far better if `stopListening` / `stop` did the right thing regardless of how far `start` had gotten.nnHowever, that would require significantly more surgery, so I will leave it to the people who work on Proxygen full-time :)nnThis diff fixes the race condition by ensuring `HTTPServer::start` does not touch `mainEventBase_` after `onSuccess` fires.nnReviewed By: agodernnDifferential Revision: D4365496nnfbshipit-source-id: 9623306f3cf5556276a6c50c49b4ad0983e0af8en

sfinae expressions generate wrong definitionsSummary:nSfinae expressions don't work properly and generate wrong definitions for the two functions.nWe can further reduce the case to the following example:nn#include <type_traits>n#include <utility>nnstruct S {ntemplate<typename T>nstd::enable_if<std::is_constructible<T>::value>nf() {}n};nnint main() {nstatic_assert(std::is_same<decltype(std::declval<S>().f<void>()), std::enable_if<false>>::value, !);nstatic_assert(std::is_same<decltype(std::declval<S>().f<int>()), std::enable_if<true>>::value, !);n}nnAs shown:nn* In the first case, the function should be rejected during substitution. Instead it is accepted with a return type `std:.enable_if<false>`.n* In the second case, the expected type is probably `void`, the actual one is `std::enable_if<true>`.nnSomething similar happens to `FilterChain::addFilters` function templates.nn ---nnI've used the same _C++11-ish_ expressions seen in the whole codebase:nntypename std::enCloses https://github.com/facebook/proxygen/pull/140nnReviewed By: yfeldblumnnDifferential Revision: D4364935nnPulled By: maxgeorgnnfbshipit-source-id: 81298af68dac7196f08da841b25839cede7fb709n

Fix the second parameter to inflateInit2Summary:nI'm compiling Proxygen on a system that has an older version of Zlibn(1.2.3). This version doesn't select a default value for windowBits whennthe value is out of range, resulting in a crash in CodecTests.nnFrom the Zlib manual:nnThe windowBits parameter is the base two logarithm of the maximumnwindow size (the size of the history buffer).  It should be in thenrange 8..15 for this version of the library. The default value is 15nif inflateInit is used instead.nnFor this fix I selected MAX_WBITS, i.e. 15, which appears to be thenvalue being used when 0 is passed in. The manual continues on:nnwindowBits can also be greater than 15 for optional gzip decoding.nAdd 32 to windowBits to enable zlib and gzip decoding with automaticnheader detection, or add 16 to decode only the gzip format (the zlibnformat will return a Z_DATA_ERROR).nnIt isn't clear to me if something extra needs to be done to enable gzipndecoding. Generalize map from client priority level to HTTP2 priority to handle arbitrary tree.Summary:nThis patch updates the proxygen virtual stream based priority scheme from the current system which allows only strict priorities to a flexible system allowing an arbitrary tree of virtual streams, subject only to the limitations in the HTTP/2 specification. An arbitrary prioritization scheme can be implemented by constructing virtual streams corresponding to the desired prioritization and attaching new streams as dependancies of the appropriate virtual stream.nnUsage:nnThe user must define a map from an opaque integer priority level to an  HTTP/2 priority corresponding to the virtual stream. This map is  implemented by the user in a class that extends `HTTPUpstreamSession::PriorityMapBuilder`. A shared pointer to this class is passed into the constructor of `HTTPUpstreamSession`. This method will send the virtual streams and return a unique pointer to a class that extends `HTTPUpstreamSession::PriorityAdapter`. This class implements the map between the user defined priority level and the HTTP/2 priority level.nnWhen the session is started, the `createVirtualStreams` method of `PriorityMapBuilder` is called by `HTTPUpstreamSession::startNow`. The returned pointer to the `PriorityAdapter` map is cached in  `HTTPUpstreamSession`. The HTTP/2 priority that should be used for a new stream dependent on a virtual stream corresponding to a given priority level is then retrieved by calling the `HTTPUpstreamSession::getHTTPPriority(uint8_t level)` method.nnThe prior strict priority system has been left in place for now, but if both maxLevels and priorityMapBuilder are passed into the `HTTPUpstreamSession` constructor, the maxLevels parameter will be ignored.nnFacebook section:nThis is the open source part of a larger effort to allow the mapping of Tigon priorities to h2. The FB part will make the builder in `HTTPClient` and pass it into the upstream session constructor. Then the request priority will be mapped to h2 priority in `HTTPTransactionAdaptor::setTransaction()`.nnReviewed By: afrindnnDifferential Revision: D5136079nnfbshipit-source-id: a69d087b0fe64348acac2ded3c69d2d3a68b2843n

Use ShipIt dependency hashes for a consistent buildSummary:nPreviously, when building e.g. Proxygen, we would check out the master branch of dependencies like Folly. This could result in version shear, and the odds of it would go up as you iterated on your branch, while the dependencies moved forward. This degrades our developer experience.nnThe solution is to actually build from the same point in Facebook's monorepo.nnAs implemented, this is still imperfect, because the in-tree dependency hashes under `build/deps/github_hashes` are not currently updated atomically. However, on balance, this predictability should still be better -- and if I recall sdwilsh's explanation correctly, the atomicity of dependency commits could be fixed if it really impacts many people.nnThis will also improve cache coherence when you're using ccache for iteration, see D5648461.nn(Also includes some extra ideas comments, and a whitespace fix.)nnReviewed By: sdwilshnnDifferential Revision: D5648388nnfbshipit-source-id: 1baa68ff3ef2e204a6cf5f5297e52514a3b62d21n

Enable ccache to speed up Travis Docker-based builds 3-4xSummary:nUnfortunately, Travis is constantly in a capacity crunch. Plus, building `folly` + `wangle` + `proxygen` + `thrift` takes upwards of 40 minutes on Travis hosts, and the timeout for builds is 50 minutes. That creates several problems:n - Builds tend to get queued up, and sometimes take a long time to produce signal.n - Adding more platform, or project, or dependency coverage to our Travis builds would just make the problem worse (so I have not pushed much on the adoption of `fbcode_builder`).n - Building a service of any complexity will likely pull in all of the above dependencies, and then it gets 10 minutes for build & tests. So higher-up-the-foodchain projects like `bistro` just time out.nnTo help accelerate builds, Travis supports caching build artifacts between runs: https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/caching/#Arbitrary-directoriesnEach build variant gets its own cache, as one would want: https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/caching/#Caches-and-build-matricesnnThis is great for us because -- especially with all the `Updating submodules` commits -- we actually keep rebuilding nearly the same tree, most of the time.nnBetter yet, https://ccache.samba.org provides transparent compile caching -- just set your cache directory (and a few options), and use `ccache {gcc,g++}` instead of the vanilla compiler. It does the rest, and is quite robust -- the only issues I had were:n - different platforms have different versions, so one has to target ccache 3.1-ish,n - the max cache size started out too small, which tended to eliminate all speedup.nnIn this diff, I enable `ccache` for all projects using the default `.travis.yml` (jstrizich, you'll need to patch the custom `.travis.yml` files of `openr` and `fbzmq` if you want to try caching).nnNotably, even if a project would time out on Travis without `ccache`, the caching accumulates across minor revisions, and should keep re-build times quite short for most changes.nnThis also significantly improves the experience of iterating on a Docker-based build on your own machine -- thoughtful use of Docker layer caching & ccache dramatically speeds up rebuilds after certain changes.nnIt works like this:n - Start with an empty `ccache.tgz`, or a pre-existing one provided by Travis from its cache.n - The `Dockerfile` extracts it into the Docker image under `/ccache`, and sets some environment variables to enable ccache for C & C++ builds.n - The build runs as usual.n - The build either finishes successfully, or it fails, or the new option of `docker_build_timeout` kills the container about 10 minutes before Travis would time out the build.n - A small script runs inside the container to prepare the updated `ccache.tgz`. This includes automatic cache sizing based on the working set size of a full successful build.n - Travis uploads `ccache.tgz` to S3 for the next build.nnThe rest is plumbing, CLI tweaks, and documentation to make manual iteration using `ccache` fairly pleasant.nnThe overhead of my `ccache` implementation is hard to measure exactly, but based on my indirect measurements, it's on the order of 2 minutes for `bistro`, which would otherwise take 52+ minutes to build on Travis.nnReviewed By: zpaonnDifferential Revision: D5648461nnfbshipit-source-id: 207b621ba6bc6f827b20a5746b4dc4f28c1c96e2n

Easy: Improve ccache sizingSummary:nWhen I was testing ccache in detail, I actually bootstrapped with a 1.8GB max cache size for Bistro. It looked like we were using only 1.2-1.3 GB uncompressed, so I figured that adaptively setting the maximum to be 30% more would be fine.nnMy two mistakes were:n - ccache uses decimal megabytes, so 30% became 25%.n - ccache's LRU is kind of lossy so your max cache size has to be a LOT larger than the real thing to avoid inducing significant misses from cache cleanups.nnI should note that ccache still did speed up both the Bistro and the Proxygen builds somewhat, but cache miss rates seem too high, especially for builds that are not changing any headers. However, the current speedups are more like 20-30% rather than 3x.nnThis is an attempt to decrease cache miss rates to 0 for no-source-change rebuilds.nnI'm not too worried about cache bloat, since (a) even 400MB tarballs should still work fine for our caches, (b) I have no evidence that ccache would actually ever get to its max.nnI also noticed & fixed that my `ccache.log` in the Docker container was empty due to permissions issues.nnReviewed By: zpaonnDifferential Revision: D5687199nnfbshipit-source-id: a500c90f0c74797e3e4c8dc17de44977d86b1b70n

So force the HPACK table to use the more memory efficient fbstring.nnReviewed By: yfeldblum, dddmellonnDifferential Revision: D5808250nnfbshipit-source-id: 2a8960822984484f227918ed819d6ca64ed60b65n

Add QCRAM support to HPACK, part 1 - seqns and epochsSummary:nSplitting this diff into three parts for reviewability.  This is implementing QCRAM support as described in https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-krasic-quic-qcram-00.nnPart 1 adds sequence numbers to the encoded blocks and epochs to the table state.  The encoder follows the rules in the draft about when an indexed header may be used.  There is an explicit API to increment the encoder's commit epoch (eg: an ack).  The default behavior is to 'auto-commit' every epoch, which assumes in-order delivery.nnReviewed By: dddmellonnDifferential Revision: D4942974nnfbshipit-source-id: 586d3d7b9b3eda36f8ee0d14f66efa968a0407e4n

Add QCRAM support to HPACK, part 2 - expose evictionsSummary: Per the spec, when a header table operation triggers an eviction, QCRAM may not be used.  Exposing via the encode APInnReviewed By: dddmellonnDifferential Revision: D4942984nnfbshipit-source-id: da313af2de5ec3ffe89ffb50fa877b4bd4c0bea3n

Add QCRAM support to HPACK, part 3 - absolute indexingSummary:nThis adds absolute indexing.  The spec is somewhat underspecified here, but my best guess it that the base index is supposed to be like an absolute version of head_.  This won't work with table resizing, but as I understand it, that's dead in the current QUIC draft.nnThe encoder calls 'markBaseIndex' and serializes the index as an HPACK integer with 0 bit prefix (previously illegal in our code).  This sets the readBaseIndex for the encoder so that all serialized indecies are relative to the starting base index.nnThe decoder calls setBaseIndex when processing a block which handles both translations for indexed header decoding (readBaseIndex) and also potentially offset adds into the table (writeBaseIndex).nnReviewed By: dddmellonnDifferential Revision: D4943055nnfbshipit-source-id: 0c33f16673305f721f55a122cb8030b301c2c649n

Change the logic to force these to literal without indexing. CompressionSimulatorSummary:nThis is a simulator to test the efficacy of the QCRAM/QPACK algorithms.  The input is a HAR file containing actual request start times and headers (such a file can be captured from a browser).  The inital set of knobs are RTT, loss rate, delay rate, max delay, and how many inital forced in-order packets to use.  You can also specify an RNG seed to compare how different algorithms fare with the same parameters.nnExamplennHPACK style (force receiver to decode in order)nn  Stats:n  Blocks sent: 185n  Allowed OOO: 0n  Packet Losses: 14n  HOL Block Count: 9n  HOL Delay (ms): 1344n  Max Queue Buffer Bytes: 1342n  Uncompressed Bytes: 137265n  Compressed Bytes: 36216n  Compression Ratio: 73nnQCRAM with same network behaviornn  Stats:n  Blocks sent: 185n  Allowed OOO: 98n  Packet Losses: 14n  HOL Block Count: 7n  HOL Delay (ms): 1004n  Max Queue Buffer Bytes: 826n  Uncompressed Bytes: 137265n  Compressed Bytes: 42902n  Compression Ratio: 68nnReviewed By: dddmellonnDifferential Revision: D4971193nnfbshipit-source-id: c2fcc53829f3d76418ad1b32b9554465eb7eacf8n

Fix codec issueSummary:nApparently the codec can generatenmore bytes that the input byte, makes sense.nnHowever in the case where thennflow control limit is very close to the numbernof pending bytes, the codec can generate bytesninto the write buffer which exceed the flow controlnlimit.nnIn this case, the txnEgressQueue doesn't have thenstream any more because the txn believes it has writtennout all the bytes, however the bytes are technically onlynpartially written out. remove encoder stream framingSummary:nThe consensus of the WG is to remove the length prefix for the encoder stream.  Therefore we need to support partial decodes.  If the buffer ends in the middle of an integer, that integer will be re-parsed each time more bytes arrive until the integer is complete.  If a literal length is parsed but the buf if shorter than the length, we discard the length and reparse it when more bytes arrive.  If we've parsed a literal name, we remember it and will re-start parsing from the value length.nnThis is somewhat suboptimal as we could remember the parsed lengths.  That would require changing the HPACKDecodeBuffer interface.  The worst case cost is that we reparse a literal's length once per byte of literal.  Room for improvement but this is a decent start.nnReviewed By: mjoras, w-o-onnDifferential Revision: D8359270nnfbshipit-source-id: 1a3b59921c5aa258d0a0356012b83c44d5842b29n

Fixes to min-freeSummary:nmin-free is the amount of space in the table to reserve for future insertions.  When the free space falls below min-free, QPACKHeaderTable increments the drainingIndex, which prevents making new references to these headers so they become evictable soon.  There are two fixesnn1) Update minFree in setCapacity - we were using the wrong values in our interop testsn2) Have a min and max minFree valuennReviewed By: mjorasnnDifferential Revision: D9819105nnfbshipit-source-id: 4423a1f7f619b47a67bbb8afac492a903b87c13en

Don't add headers that would immediately drainSummary: Any header that is immediately draining (eg: the header is larger than capacity - minFree) would never be used in compression.  Don't waste bytes on the wire by encoding them.  Note that because kMinFree is 48 and the minimum size of a header is 32, any tables smaller than 80 bytes can never hold a value.nnReviewed By: mjoras, lnicconnDifferential Revision: D9819102nnfbshipit-source-id: 0e81508b1040954088403168e7b79c2c9a227f53n

Don't evict unacknowledged headersSummary:nWe had an issue in interop with non-blocking decoders and small tables.  The encoder would speculatively insert headers it *would* have indexed, but because there was no reference to it, there was nothing preventing the headers from being evicted by the encoder.  This would happen before the decoder acknowledged the insert, so there were lots of inserts but never any references to the table.nnNow we require the header to be acknowledged before it becomes evictable.  This improved compression with very small tables (256 bytes) from -11% to 60%.nnReviewed By: mjorasnnDifferential Revision: D9819103nnfbshipit-source-id: 0179e4bf330cb784087f1b37f579ceec6707f139n

Update QPACKInterop to handle HAR or QIF files.Summary:nThis was possibly uglier than just making two copies of the interop program.nn+ Refactored the file reading loop so it could be used for parsing QIF or compressed files (Reader/CompressedReader/QIFReader).n+ Refactored encoding loop so HAR is converted to a vector of blocks.  This is bloaty but's just driver coden+ There's a new streaming callback for decoding compressed files that outputs a QIF.nnReviewed By: mjorasnnDifferential Revision: D9819106nnfbshipit-source-id: ce7f0016346c2f65a23ff5ec24005cc1e7f914f6n

Simulate TSS for non-blocking decoders in immediate ack modeSummary: When the simulator is using non-blocking mode with immediate acks, it is performing table inserts but not referencing those headers in header blocks.  The decoder must emit a Table State Sync instruction to tell the encoder the headers are available for use.  To do this correctly, we need to run the decoder during encoding.nnReviewed By: mjoras, lnicconnDifferential Revision: D9819104nnfbshipit-source-id: 925ace124d65dabf90012f6ddc6a9ab9c98af504n

setMaxTableSize also changes table capacitySummary: If an encoder violates the protocol because it thinks the table is larger than the decoder's, it will result in an INVALID_INDEX reference when trying to decode the evicted header.  setMaxTableSize previously only set the maximum allowed value in a Table Size Update instruction.  Now it will also update the decoder's table size.nnReviewed By: mjorasnnDifferential Revision: D12910777nnfbshipit-source-id: 3be303b935874828fab4c7079c320d4075d9b822n

Prevent deadlock on encoder streamSummary:nThere's a nasty potential deadlock in HQ, where encoding a header block produces more output on the control stream than is available in its stream flow control window.  Depending on the egress pattern and amount of connection flow control remaining, the peer may receive a header block but never receive the control data it depends on.nnThis diff tells the encoder the maximum amount of control bytes it can generate that are referenceable by the stream block.  Once flow control is exhausted, the encoder will not insert any new values.  It will still process duplicates normally, but won't reference a duplicate if it didn't fit.nnReviewed By: lnicconnDifferential Revision: D12903121nnfbshipit-source-id: 8f1c896f2340d1a7940a20b6d95c1513ad7fc8a6n

Delay applying decoder max table size until SETTINGS-ACKSummary:nWe were always cheating a little with this part of the spec.  The sender of the SETTINGS is not supposed to apply them until it receives the ACK.  So it's possible that a peer could have sent some headers encoded with the default (4k) header table, while a SETTINGS frame lowering the value was in flight.  This decode could have failed.nnThis is only the beginning or a partial fix for the issue.nn1. It only applies to one setting, the dynamic table size.n2. It doesn't support more than one SETTING frame in flightn3. There is no timeout on the SETTINGS-ACKnnReviewed By: lnicconnDifferential Revision: D12894342nnfbshipit-source-id: f952209f4fa355d604b71c420a0e9552237b787bn

isExpectingWindowUpdate -> isExpectingIngressSummary:nWe've observed cases with extremely stale (several days old) sessions hanging around. This appears to be caused by the fact that our send window is full and ingress was paused. The current logic for `isExpectingIngress`seems somewhat backwards, and in this situation causes us to never schedule the transaction timeout if our ingress is paused. This changes is to make it so that if we are expecting a window update then we are expecting ingress. This should prevent us from never timing out the transaction in the case that we never receive a window update.nnNote that while this should address the problem of sessions growing out of control, it doesn't explain why we get so many sessions that end up like this in the first place.nnReviewed By: afrindnnDifferential Revision: D13466182nnfbshipit-source-id: b60f3b79ef0b7733c947d45eac336068b03bb266n

Capture session byte offset for first and last body bytesSummary:nAdds support for capturing the session byte offset of the first and last bytes of a response body.nnProtocols that support preemption and multiplexing (e.g., HTTP/2) may write multiple response body in parallel to the transport. Capturing the first and last body byte offsets enables examination of this multiplexing.nnThe difference between these two offsets is also useful for measuring throughput as it provides the total number of bytes transferred via transport between the time the first byte of the response was flushed (`TransportInfo::timeToFirstByte`) and when the ack was received for the last byte in the response (`TransportInfo::timeToLastBodyByteAck`).nnNotes:n- Added new functions to `HTTPTransactionTransportCallback` callback interface instead of adding parameters to `firstByteFlushed` and `lastByteFlushed` to avoid breaking existing code. New functions are not pure virtual.n- `onEgressBodyFirstByte` and `onEgressBodyLastByte` are called in `HTTPSessionBase::commonEom` (via `HTTPSessionBase::handleLastByteEvents`) and in `ByteEventTracker::processByteEvents`. Only capturing / including the offsets when called by `processByteEvents`, as the offset has already been recorded in the `ByteEvent` objects.nnReviewed By: udippantnnDifferential Revision: D14731317nnfbshipit-source-id: b66517817d46442bd81bf88b8edf250966efc56cn

Framework for tracking when first/last response byte sent by NICSummary:nToday we record a timestamp when the first and last bytes are written to the kernel buffer by a call to `send()` in the `folly::AsyncSocket` transport layer [1]. Because HTTP/2 supports pipelining, the kernel send buffer may not be empty when the first/last byte of a response is written via `send()` and as a result the byte may spend significant time in the buffer (depends on the client's throughput, latency, and socket LOWAT configuration).nnThis diff adds the framework for tracking when the NIC actually sends / transmits (TX) the first and last byte of a response via kernel timestamps.nnThis is useful for:n- analyzing how long response bytes are waiting in the kernel send buffer for HTTP/2 connections, which may help determine if the `LOWAT` setting for the socket is optimal for HTTP/2n- determining throughput, as it enables the time in the kernel send buffer to be accounted for in the total duration and enables adjacent responses to be coalesced when there are no gaps in the send queuenn[1] The timestamps are triggered via the following chain: `AsyncSocket::writeImpl` -> `HTTPSession::WriteSegment::writeSuccess` (callback implementation for `AsyncSocket::WriteCallback`) -> `ByteEventTracker::processByteEvents` -> `HTTPTransaction::onEgressBodyFirstByte`.nnReviewed By: siyengarnnDifferential Revision: D14998833nnfbshipit-source-id: 42408d9c56a0419c60ecf1306b577d16ff4219adn

Plumbing for TX timestamp tracking (addTxByteEvent, onFirstByteEvent)Summary:nAdds plumbing required for TX timestamp tracking:n- `ByteEventTracker::addTxByteEvent` can be used to create an event for tracking TX of the first or last byten- `ByteEventTracker::processByteEvents` will now call `ByteEventTracker::Callback::onFirstByteEvent` when the first byte has been inserted into the sent buffer. The callback handler for `onFirstByteEvent` and `onLastByteEvent` can call `ByteEventTracker::addTxByteEvent` to create an event to track the TX of the byte.n- `HTTPSession::onFirstByteEvent` has been implemented to call `addTxByteEvent` when EOR tracking is enabled.n- `ByteEventTracker::presend` and `HTTPSession::getNextToSend` function signatures now includes `som` (start of message), which is similar to `eom`. TX timestamps are requested for `som` and `eom` in HTTPSession, and ACK timestamps are requested for eom.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D15098998nnfbshipit-source-id: 663f65c0620f53d62d5934f550509446ca6cc267n

Fix offset in calls to addFirstBodyByteEventSummary:n`HTTPSession::sendBody` and `HQSession::HQStreamTransportBase::sendBody` call `ByteEventTracker::addFirstBodyByteEvent` when the first body byte of a transaction is being sent. However, the offset the both pass is off by one.nn`HTTPSession:sendBody` uses the value of `sessionByteOffset()` while `HQSession::HQStreamTransportBase::sendBody` uses `streamByteOffset()`. Both of these are the offset of the last byte written to the transport. The first byte of the body is the _next_ byte written to the transport, which means that 1 should be added to either of these values.nnThis hasn't caused problems in the past because `ByteEventTracker::processByteEvents(..., uint64_t bytesWritten)` processes any events with offsets <= bytesWritten. However, this incorrect offset creates problems when adding TX timestamping for the first body byte.nnReviewed By: siyengarnnDifferential Revision: D15114466nnfbshipit-source-id: 7ec11348f233b3edf0919330265ea4c97da6a2d6n

Send firstByteOffset/lastByteOffset before firstByteFlushed/lastByteFlushedSummary: Unidirectional EX_STREAMS consider last byte flushed as end of transaction. We should send byteOffset info before calling these callbacks since the downstream can terminate transportCallback_.nnReviewed By: bolekknnDifferential Revision: D15187281nnfbshipit-source-id: 8055c1529f7de3d3890a227bab691edbb82b99edn

It does this by reading shipitnmapping information from the manifest file for the project.nnSince this fetcher uses data in the manifest and is implementedndirectly in the getdeps codebase, it is suitable for iteratingnon the opensource builds directly out of fbsource on both devserversnand laptops inside FB.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14691012nnfbshipit-source-id: 05f68a7be64a2e465937b24b8825d25d3348ed13n

You can look around, make experimentalnchanges and commit them, and you can discard any commits you make in thisnstate without impacting any branches by performing another checkout.nnIf you want to create a new branch to retain commits you create, you mayndo so (now or later) by using -b with the checkout command again. Example:nn  git checkout -b <new-branch-name>nnHEAD is now at 470344d Merge pull request #1479 from facebook/visualTestn ---n+ git -C /data/users/wez/scratch/dataZusersZwezZfbsource/fbcode_builder_getdeps/repos/github.com-facebook-zstd.git submodule update --initn```nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14691008nnfbshipit-source-id: 3afa391360518a08ebd6ff97f5b8b4993f10c4e8n

fbcode_builder: getdeps: add list-deps subcommandSummary:nWhile the command isn't necessarily super usefulnon its own, it does show that the plumbing for walking thendeps is functioning, and that is important when it comesnto building.nnThe output lists the projects in the order that theynwould be built.nnThe `fetch` command has been augmented to add a `--recursive`nflag that uses the same mechanism to recursively fetchnthe dependencies.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14691004nnfbshipit-source-id: b00bf6ad4742f8bb0a70698f71a5fe03d6a1f453n

The `cmake.defines` section ofnthe manifest is used to pass `-Dkey=value` options to the cmake configurencommand line.nnWe prefer to use `ninja` to execute the build so that we can use morencores than 1 on Windows and just for consistency across platformsnwith mac and linux.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14690998nnfbshipit-source-id: 8102e8b4a47da515ca001772788ed0e5f2645ad7n

fbcode_builder: getdeps: add NinjaBootstrap builderSummary:nthis builder is used to bootstrap the ninja build tool.nnOn Windows and mac the manifest for ninja is set to download a pre-built executable.nWhile pre-built executables are available for linux they aren't portable enoughnfor our purposes so we need to be able to build it for ourselves.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14690992nnfbshipit-source-id: b60fd02ad04f58dc7c2931280341791270609737n

fbcode_builder: getdeps: add OpenSSL builderSummary:nthe openssl builder knows how to perform the non-standardnconfiguration and build steps to build openssl.nnOn Linux systems the manifests for our projects don't mentionnopenssl, causing them to pick up the system openssl.nnOn Mac, apple don't ship openssl headers so we need to build our own.nOn Windows there is no standard openssl installation so we also neednto build our own.nnAs a result, this builder only works on windows and mac.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14691010nnfbshipit-source-id: 9f8979f9eaeb5209c290cf4f43c97c0cb43d13a2n

fbcode_builder: getdeps: add Boost builderSummary:nthe boost builder knows how to perform the non-standardnconfigure and build for boost.nnIdeally we'd just build this statically and be happy but there arensome nuances I've observed while building on different platforms:nn* One of our projects (thrift or wangle) explicitly requests staticn  boost linkage for reasons unspecifiedn* on darwin the install_name is broken when building dynamic libsnnFor the sake of expediency in getting getdeps up and running, thensolution for the moment is to build static on posix systems andnbuild both static and shared on windows systems.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14691009nnfbshipit-source-id: 634770a6f53c3ada42d1877cc6c3dacc6eed7d18n

getdeps: add build subcommandSummary:nadds the command that is used to drive a build.nnThe dependencies of the named project are computed usingnthe same mechanism behind the `list-deps` subcommand.nIf a manifest specifies that it uses the `cmake` builder thenna dependency on `cmake` is synthesized so that we can downloadna recent version of cmake ahead of time.nnThe build command uses the fetcher to update the src and thennexecutes the builder.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14691011nnfbshipit-source-id: 31ae59614651ef021a9505e89c13b5717b440071n

fbcode_builder: getdeps: add `sandcastle` subcommandSummary:nThis command schedules a facebook specific sandcastle job for the currentncommit in your repo for each of the platforms we have support for innsandcastle.nnYou can use `--dry-run` to have it print out the job specs.nnTo support this, I've moved around some of the support utilitiesnto make it easier to import them.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14710330nnfbshipit-source-id: fb1e2a2ce78e52894291159514977da97028b37fn

fbcode_builder: getdeps: beef up hash computationSummary:npreviously, a relatively lame hash was computed to usenfor the build directory based on some hash of the source directory.nThat was good enough to get things off the ground, but in theninterest of being able to cache the build outputs and safelyninvalidate them we need a slightly more rigorous implementation.nnThis diff computes a hash based on the manifest contents andnrelevant environmental factors.nnThe hash is used to name the build directory which will ultimatelynbe cached eg: using the travis/appveyor cache directory configurationnand some other means for the FB internal CI.nnThe hash needs to be sufficient that we change the hash whennthe manifests change.  We can tolerate a false positive changenin hash (it just means that a build will take longer), butncannot tolerate a false negative (which would result in annincorrect build).nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14710332nnfbshipit-source-id: ebc2e74eafc6f3305d4412a82195bc9fb9dfa615n

fbcode_builder: getdeps: introduce loader classSummary:nThe loader makes it possible to monkey patch the functionsnthat are responsible for loading manifests. fbcode_builder: getdeps: use testpilot when available to record testsSummary:nIf `testpilot` is available, generate a buck compatible json file describing the available test binaries and feed that to testpilot to have it run the tests.nnA later (yet to be written) diff will be able to pass appropriate flags down to testpilot in continuous runs and that will allow testpilot to auto-disable and file tasks for tests in the opensource builds.nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D14766856nnfbshipit-source-id: 4e144ff18f6788cf5e830d29788eabd2dbbae46an

Reduce noisy logging when we get buffer underflowsSummary:nWe log errors when we receive partial table update or partial duplicate instructions, even though we correctly handle these two cases.nnHere's a short explanation of why our handling of these two cases is correct: In either case, we set the value of partial_.consumed to be the bytes consumed before we parse that instruction (https://fburl.com/z69a7s2s). If we get a buffer underflow, we only consume the bytes that were consumed prior to the instruction that led to the buffer underflow (https://fburl.com/ggd5pmrd). The value of partial_.consumed isn't modified within either of these two cases.nnReviewed By: afrindnnDifferential Revision: D15271146nnfbshipit-source-id: b92b40871a75fc8afd74f80b7c1a484a4534d6d9n

Reuse old build dir on WindowsSummary:ngetdeps.py's find_existing_win32_subst_for_path function tries to reuse an existing build directory alias. (On Windows, the build directory is aliased to a drive letter to shorten paths.) If this function does not find and existing build directory alias, getdeps.py invalidates many of its caches.nnOn my Windows machine, find_existing_win32_subst_for_path always fails, so all of my builds are super slow. This happens because find_existing_win32_subst_for_path is given a path with a lower-case drive letter (c:users...), but the subst command returns paths with an upper-case drive letter (C:users...).nnWhen comparing paths, use ntpath.normpath. This makes the comparison case-insensitive for drive letters. (It also makes the comparison case-insensitive for other path components.)nnOn Linux and macOS, this diff should not change behavior.nnReviewed By: weznnDifferential Revision: D15466096nnfbshipit-source-id: 1669aa0a6eaeb6012154f3a9e24eba3f835262c6n

Introducing unidirectional stream dispatcherSummary:n## contextnIn preparation of merging the `draft-20` peek-based dispatching for the unidirectional streams with the `nascent streams` which will be brought by the ServerPush, I am introducing a new abstraction - `UnidirectionalStreamReadDispatcher`nnThe abstraction roughly follows the [`ChainOfResponsibility`](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain-of-responsibility_pattern) design pattern.n## detailed explanationnThe `Dispatcher` owns assigning the correct callbacks to streams based on the preface. It interacts with the HQSession via its callback interface - this is done intentionally so that it will be easy to test the dispatcher.nnWhen a new stream is available, the `HQSesssion` assigns the dispatcher as a `PeekCallback` to the (not yet identified stream).nnOnce a preface is read (or it is confirmed that there is no preface, see below), the `Dispatcher` notifies the `HQSession` which callback should be used for that stream. `HQSession` is expected to assign the callback to the stream.nnTwo separate cases are distinguished:n 1. The `Dispatcher` assigns a read callback (via `assignReadCallback`). This is used for the control streams.n 2. The `Dispatcher` assigns a peek callback (via `assignPeekCallback`).nnThe latter method is used for both the unframed portion of the push stream, and for the grease streams (see footnote 1)nnAs the data arrives to on the stream, it is being passed to the appropriate callback, where it is processed according to the stream type:n * For control streams, the data is being processed in the same way it is done today.n * For the nascent push streams (peek callback), the unframed push id is peeked. Once read, a nascent stream object is created, as a part of the late binding process.n * For the grease streams, the data is peeked, and consumed, without any attempt to parse it.nn  +------------------------+ +----------------------+n  || |Unidirectional Stream |n  ||   new stream--->|   Read Dispatcher|--+n  |   HQSession|---available |  |  |n  || +----------------------+  |n  || | |n  +------------------------+ | |n   ^ | |n   | | |n  +-----callback available for sream--------+ |n |n   +--------------------+|n   |   Control Stream   ||n   |  callback  |<---+n   +--------------------+|n |n   +--------------------+|n   |   NasPush Stream   ||n   |  callback  |<---+n   +--------------------+|n |n   +--------------------+|n   |   Grease Stream||n   |  callback  |<---+n   +--------------------+nn[footnote 1]  for the grease streams using a peek/consume becomes more efficient when there is a missing data block. With the peek/consume API, the data is dumped ASAP, vs. relying on the transport to reliably retransmit the missing data block - thus saving both the memory, and the timers.nnReviewed By: mjorasnnDifferential Revision: D15312250nnfbshipit-source-id: f79eca1ebb3ed2bccd80371c497c8fe8d8e2357dn

Using different lookup methods for ingress/egressSummary:nNow that we have more stream types than just `HQStreamTransport` and `HQControlStream`, we need to make sense of which stream is used where.nnTo do so, I have replaced the majority of direct accesses to `streams_` map with intent-based methods, e.g. `getIngressStreams` - which is called whenever a read event needs to be propagated.nnThe methods are:n  // Finds any transport-like stream that has not been detachedn  // by quic stream idn  HQStreamTransportBase* findNonDetachedStream(quic::StreamId streamId);nn  //  Find any transport-like stream by quic stream idn  HQStreamTransportBase* findStream(quic::StreamId streamId);nn  // Find any transport-like stream suitable for ingress (request/push-ingress)n  HQStreamTransportBase* findIngressStream(nquic::StreamId streamId, bool includeDetached=false);nn  // Find any transport-like stream suitable for egress (request/push-egress)n  HQStreamTransportBase* findEgressStream(nquic::StreamId streamId, bool includeDetached=false);nn  // Find an ingress push streamn  HQIngressPushStream* findIngressPushStream(quic::StreamId);n  HQIngressPushStream* findIngressPushStreamByPushId(quic::StreamId);nn  // Find an ingress push streamn  HQEgressPushStream* findEgressPushStream(quic::StreamId);n  HQEgressPushStream* findEgressPushStreamByPushId(quic::StreamId);nn  // Erase the stream. Returns true if the streamn  // has been erasedn  bool eraseStream(quic::StreamId);nn  // Find a control stream by typen  HQControlStream* findControlStream(hq::UnidirectionalStreamType streamType);nn  // Find a control stream by stream id (either ingress or egress)n  HQControlStream* findControlStream(quic::StreamId streamId);nnI have considered isolating these methods into a separate class, but this depends on the stream types being de-coupled from the `HQSession`. Until the strong coupling exists, these methods have to be implemented by the `HQSession` itself.nnCommit notes:n- introduced methods for looking up ingress/egress streamsn- transitioned HQSession::processStreamData to use `findIngressStream` instead of direct accessn- transitioned HQSession::onDeliveryAck to use `findEgressStream` instead of direct accessn- transitioned HQSession::onCanceled to use `findEgressStream` instead of direct accessn- transitioned HQSession::createStreamTransport to rely on `findStream` instead of direct accessn- added HQSession::eraseStream to avoid having to manually look up the stream in then  right binn- transitioned HQSession::timeoutExpired to check ingress/egress streams as welln- extended HQSession::pauseTransactions to pause egressPushStreams_ along with the normal streamsn- transitioned HQSession::onFlowControlUpdate to update all egress streams, not only request streamsnnReviewed By: lnicconnDifferential Revision: D15053546nnfbshipit-source-id: b9de3b4702f11c8824951172f9dd298189f64aden

Binding ingress streams to nascent streamsSummary:nThis diff completes the reception of incoming push streams:nnHQSession is managing the reception of the stream, including the preface parsing.nnActual creation of the push stream is delegated to the server push lifecycle mediator, which can decide whether a new ingress stream is created. This is done for two reasons:nn1. Separation of the policy from the parsing allows careful testing of both in isolationn2. In the anticipation of the fast video playback, different strategies may be useful:n- As a default strategy, the creation of the ingress stream object is deferred until both push promise and push stream preface has been received.n- However, it will be possible to redefine that strategy, with for example, fast forwarding of whitelisted push ids, in which case the ingress push stream can be created before the push promise has been received. This functionality is out of scope of the MVP.nnOutline of the process (to be followed by a proper diagram).nn- Every unidirectional stream starts as a synchronous streamn- Once the stream is recognized as a push stream via the Stream Type constant, a new Nascent push stream object is allocated.n- The Nascent push stream is responsible for reading the preface.n- Once the preface has been read, the nascent push stream is paused, and the lifecycle callback is notified on the new existing push stream. If no lifecycle callback is set,nnOnce the MVP is done, adding a proper SM will help ensuring the high qualitynnReviewed By: lnicconnDifferential Revision: D14582551nnfbshipit-source-id: cd65882cc19c9800bcbd0c4540246b35d501ed9cn

HTTPConnector: Allow for HTTPCodecFactories that return nullptrSummary: There's a use case where a client wants to fail to establish a connection unless it's HTTP/2. Disable + drain timestamp events when reads are shutdownSummary:nThis change adds logic to disable and drain any pending timestamp events when reads are shutdown. These timestamps cannot be received after reads are shutdown, so we must disable / drain or connection shutdown will stall.nnShutdown of an HTTP session is delayed if there are any pending byte tracker events. This ensures that we wait until write events have completed, but it also causes us to wait for other events such as socket timestamps. For instance, if we are waiting for a timestamp of the last byte ack (TTLBA), shutdown of the HTTP session will be delayed until either the timestamp arrives or the tracker event timeout.nnBecause of how libevent and folly::AsyncSocket work, the read callback must be installed to receive socket error messages (which include socket timestamp messages). However, we remove the read callback (shutdown reads) at various points in a connection's lifecycle. For instance, if the session has an error, or if the codec indicates that the session is not reusable (e.g., an HTTP/1.1 request with `Connection: close` in the headers, or an H2 request with a GOAWAY). Because of this, shutdown of HTTP sessions can be stalled on timestamp events that will never arrive. This creates a large problem in cases with `Connection: close`, as the client uses the connection closing as a signal that the response is complete and ends up stalling.nnNotes:n- The underlying libevent library does not have a specific event type / registration for the error messages used to communicate timestamps -- it reuses the READ and WRITE types (1). This makes it impossible to register exclusively for error messages and is the reason why we must remain registered for read events (e.g., having a read callback installed) to get timestamps.n- We could install a dummy read callback when shutting down reads instead of removing it entirely. This would allow us to still receive timestamps, but it also removes the back pressure on the connection that explicitly shutting down reads creates. We could do a two phase approach (install dummy callback, and if client is non-complaint, drain and shutdown entirely), but this doesn't seem to be worth the complexity at the moment.nn(1) https://github.com/libevent/libevent/blob/33053cdd8a9e1a7330b47759dee9cb209bed8f1b/epoll.c#L489-L490nnReviewed By: afrindnnDifferential Revision: D15441935nnfbshipit-source-id: ca357c732b86d78ff2758799395cbf92e097c792n

fix handling of common argumentsSummary:ngetdeps allowed common arguments to be specified either before or afternthe subcommand name.  However, the arguments were only actually honorednif they were specified on the command line after the subcommand name.nSpecifying any of these arguments before the subcommand would simply benignored, and the default value would be used.  This happened since thensubcommand argument's default value overwrote the value specified by thenuser from the main command parser.nnThis fixes the behavior by using `argparse.SUPPRESS` so that argparsenwon't set the value at all if it was not specified.  This allows thenvalue from the main parser to be used correctly if the argument was notnseen by the subcommand parser.nnReviewed By: chadaustinnnDifferential Revision: D16435358nnfbshipit-source-id: f3893ef7a27fb018247f249f313d6438472e0140n
