Standardize approach for handling TX and ACK timestampsSummary: We currently have different approaches for handling TX and ACK timestamps, including different ByteEvent classes and processing logic. Standardizing on TimestampByteEvent.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D15549379nnfbshipit-source-id: 1aac53505f11fcf131dd613ff7c665c9b7438c13n

Drop (som|eom)EventProcessed from ByteEventTrackerSummary:nByte trackers that perform TX and ACK timestamp tracking need to know the next byte requiring timestamping when `preSend` is called. `somEventProcessed` and `eomEventProcessed` enable these byte trackers to maintain a cache of the next `FIRST_BYTE` and `LAST_BYTE` events respectively. However, this approach makes it difficult to support timestamping for other arbitrary bytes / events as it requires careful synchronization between the base ByteEventTracker and the caches held in the derived trackers, and it makes logic in `preSend` increasingly complex.nnThis diff changes existing `preSend` implementations so that they no longer cache the next event. Instead, `preSend` implementations will simply search from the start of the byte events until they find the next event that requires timestamping (according to the tracker's respective configuration) or reach the end of the list of byte events. In practice this adds very little overhead given that most events inserted do require tracking and allows us to avoid a good amount of error-prone complexity.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16547451nnfbshipit-source-id: bffbbd6b96f696fae681358172676f51270030a5n

Make getNextToSend and preSend more genericSummary:nChanges `HTTPSession::getNextToSend` and `ByteEventTracker::preSend` to make it easier to timestamp on arbitrary bytes and to consolidate control of timestamping logic in the byte tracker.nnCurrent approach:n- `HTTPSession::getNextToSend` (called by `HTTPSession::runLoopCallback()`) and `ByteEventTracker::preSend` (called by `getNextToSend`) currently take `som` and `eom` as parameters.n- `preSend` sets `som` if it splits an IO response buffer at the start / first body byte of a response and `eom` if it splits at the end / last body byte of a response. (`som` = start of message, `eom` = end of message).n- `runLoopCallback` looks at these flags to determine if TX timestamping or ACK timestamping `WriteFlags` should be set on the `WriteSegment` based on what timestamps it believes is / should be tracked.nnProblems:n1. `som` and `eom` are not generalizable -- if you want to timestamp an arbitrary byte (let's say every other packet to get an idea of jitter), what do you do? It's neither the start or the end of the message.n2. Related to (1), `runLoopCallback` currently decides which timestamping is enabled based on `som` and `eom`. But the byte tracker controls what timestamping is possible (e.g., whether it is possible to timestamp on TX or ACK). This creates a weird maze of timestamping logic.nnDiff change:n- Change `som` and `eom` to `timestampTx` and `timestampAck` and have the byte tracker explicitly state which timestamping should be performed.n- `runLoopCallback` just sets the corresponding flags on the `WriteSegment` it has no logic of its own.nnOther changes:n- Some stat changes required to handle the new presend logicnn----nnFunction definitionsn```nHTTPSession::getNextToSend(bool* cork, bool* som, bool* eom)nByteEventTracker::preSend(bool* corkm bool* timestampTx, bool* timestampAck, uint64_t bytesWritten)n```nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16547952nnfbshipit-source-id: e75819d7d47352099dead0562af5726de06b9c71n

Split TransactionByteEvent into separate targetSummary: It's currently not possible for the `HTTPTransaction` class to interact with `ByteEvent` objects due to a dependency loop that is created if `HTTPTransaction.h` includes `ByteEvents.h`. This isn't resolvable with forward declarations. Resolving this loop by shifting the `TransactionByteEvent` class (which references `HTTPTransaction`) is shifted into a separate class.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16550297nnfbshipit-source-id: f6c76b8b9494d54d8bc6388f39c81c212974336dn

Make addAckByteEvent genericSummary: Allow the event type (`ByteEvent::EventType`) to be passed to `addAckByteEvent` so that ACK byte events can be added for byte events other than LAST_BYTE. This is required to facilitate ACK timestamping of arbitrary bytes.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16587753nnfbshipit-source-id: 3398e3f03e7d7c4f70a8cf9df691bc2ac5c0f8een

Explicitly indicate TX / ACK timestamping and merge callbacksSummary:nProblems:n1) We currently have individual callbacks specified for each ByteEvent event type associated that can have TX or ACK timestamping (`onFirstByteEvent` and `onLastByteEvent`). `HTTPSession` has to implement each of these callbacks and the result is duplicate / repetitive logic.n2) The callbacks implemented for HTTPSession don't know what timestamps (e.g., TX or ACK) are enabled / supported by the byte event tracker and ends up adding timestamping events based on the event type (e.g., first or last byte).n3) (1) and (2) combined make it harder to add in new timestamping events (e.g., timestamp every Xth byte).nnChanges:n- Each `ByteEvent` now has a `timestampTx_` and `timestampAck_` field that explicitly indicates if the tracker has requested TX or ACK timestamping.n- `ByteEventTracker::Callback::(onFirstByteEvent|onLastByteEvent)` are merged together into a single callback, `onTxnByteEventWrittenToBuf` that takes the actual `ByteEvent` instead of a subset of its fields.n- `HTTPSession::onTxnByteEventWrittenToBuf` looks at the new fields to determine what timestamping events to add.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16554985nnfbshipit-source-id: d074c3134ab5250fe7a13a00dddb00b6ea49b344n

Streamline / generalize transaction TX/ACK timestamp functionsSummary:nThis diff streamlines the callbacks used for reporting TX / ACK timestamps and byte offsets in `HTTPTransaction::TransportCallback` and `HTTPTransaction`.nnWe currently have the following callbacks in `HTTPTransaction::TransportCallback`:n- firstByteTXn- lastByteTXn- lastByteAckedn- firstByteOffsetn- lastByteOffsetnnAdding a new timestamping event (such as time to first byte ACKed, or time to Nth byte TXed) would require yet another specialized callback.nnTo resolve this, I'm replacing the above callbacks with two new, general-purpose functions: `trackedByteEventTX` and `trackedByteEventAck`. These two functions take the `ByteEvent` as a parameter and use the event type to determine how to process the event. All of the functions above except for `lastByteAcked` are replaced by these two new functions -- `lastByteAcked` is deeply baked into a few things and will take more time to transition.nnLikewise, we currently have specialized, event-type specific callbacks in `HTTPTransaction` such as `onEgressBodyFirstByteTX` and `onEgressBodyLastByteTX`. Consolidated these into `onEgressTrackedByteEventTX` and `onEgressTrackedByteEventAck`.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16550529nnfbshipit-source-id: c56917d987533746ff2a4d4ff4e0932daa8cf6e4n

Capture TX + ACK timestamps for second to last packetSummary:nAdd TX and ACK timestamping for the 2nd to last packet. This enables us to calculate a transfer duration that is not impacted / inflated due to delayed ACKs.nn- TCP may delay sending an ACK if there is only a single packet to ACK. In general TCP will delay until it has two packets to ACK or until a timeout has passed.n- Imagine if a transaction contains 11 packets. When the last packet arrives at the client, TCP may delay sending the ACK for it as there's only a single packet to ACK for. This increases the transaction's transfer time and for small transactions with low RTT and fast bottleneck links this delay can be significant relative to the total transfer time.n- One way to understand the impact of delayed ACKs is to measure the TX and ACK times for the 2nd to last packet (SLP). If the last packet's (LP) ACK is delayed, then (SLP_ACK - SLP_TX) will be lower than (LP_ACK - LP_TX) by the ACK delay time. This assumes pipelining and that SLP and LP were transmitted at about the same time.n- For throughput calculations, using the time to the ACK for the 2nd to last packet and reducing the number of bytes transferred by 1 packet's payload reduces the impact of any ACK delays on throughput calculations.nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16590958nnfbshipit-source-id: 2b00d7077b06da54299e515bfe7196e792eb8dafn

Cleaning up some state for upcoming changesSummary:nLargely a rejigger of D16013271 (Jay Edgar).nnWe mentioned we would have to do this because the out parameter breaks the flexibility of the interface in line with upcoming changes.  Namely:nn- It's business logic that we choose the max of the individual probabilities; we should be free to change this if needed and a caller shouldn't care (and we may indeed change this / expect changes with the introduction of request rate limiting).  By forcing this through the interface, it may be misleading to callers whats actually going on under the hood if we keep the code around.  Other callers were also paying a very minor cost.n- Callers should utilize the counters instead (set an instance of LoadStats) for production level tracking.n- The returned data was a dup of what is already present in wangle::LoadShedConfiguration and what is present in ResourceStats/Data.  We don't want to have dup data polluting the class and that can lead to problems down the road.nnSo I've changed the API to instead allow a caller to specifically request which resource metrics are under pressure.  And so callers who explicitly want this information will be the only ones who exercise this path and can build any supplemental information with data they already posses.nnThis will allow us to iterate rapidly on the main interface during the interim.nnI think this is what Maxim Georgiev hinted at originally too and we need to proceed given the changes planned.nnReviewed By: jalopezsilvannDifferential Revision: D16467397nnfbshipit-source-id: 1f3f40fe55f65914a7ac9da66bc04ac309dfe43fn

Detect if egress rate limited by ingressSummary:nIf a transaction is received from an upstream (ingress) slower than it is written to the downstream (egress), then the egress rate (throughput) will be limited.nnWe can detect this situation by keeping track of whether there are bytes available in a transaction's egress buffer after the transaction's first body byte has been written. This diff adds a callback to the write loop to trigger checks of ongoing transactions.nnA transaction is marked as having its egress rate limited by ingress if:n1. The body is in the process of being written to the session buffer (first byte has been written, last byte has not)n2. There are no bytes in the transaction's egress buffer (which signals that we are waiting on bytes from the upstream)nnReviewed By: sharma95nnDifferential Revision: D16935255nnfbshipit-source-id: cab2e4004dbc88564201f11b80524a8255f8b6d0n

Let's try a github action to build things (#743)Summary:nThis commit adds a getdeps command that is able to generatena workflow file for the GitHub Actions CI environment.nnThe workflow file could be expressed more simply using the matrixnsyntax and with three steps (checkout, build, test), but I chose tonbreak out the steps for each of the dependencies because the UXnwhile waiting on the build is much nicer that way: the steps shownduring and live log tailing for the section of the build that isnunderway. Fix an edge case related to HTTP pipeliningSummary:nThere were two small bugs coming from HTTPSession::detach() that would result in reading from the socket even though we should be in the anti-pipelining (paused) state.nnFirst, there's logic to call resumeIngress() there, which can result in an automatic call to resumeReads without checking the anti-pipeline state.nnSecond, maybeResumePausedPipelineTransaction() returned true only when the transaction was resumed.  I've changed the logic to return true if there is pipelining going on.  detach() has a snippet like:nn```nif (maybeResumePausedPipelineTransaction()) {n  return;n} else {n  resumeReads();n}n```nnSo it could resume from the anti-pipeline state here too.nnTo trigger this, either the underlying AsyncSocket has to have delayed the onWriteSuccess call that releases the LAST_BYTE event, or other customized ByteEventTracker behavior.nnReviewed By: lnicconnDifferential Revision: D18020595nnfbshipit-source-id: 9099f5bd8591130a5f581c6734e9789534fc2ef7n

HttpMessageFilters have the pause/resume signal.Summary:nThis changes things so that the filters are bidirectional (callbacks like onBody() flow one way, while pause/resume signals flow the other way)nn```n+-------------+onBody+-------------+onBody+-------------+onBody+-------------+n| |<-------------| |<-------------| |<-------------| |n|  TxnHandler |  |  Filter 1   |  |  Filter 2   |  | Txn |n| |  | |------------->| |------------->| |n+-------------+  +-------------+ pause/resume +-------------+ pauseIngress +-------------+n```nnBy default, a filter simply passes on the pause() and resume() signal off to the previous filter.n- **pause** indicates that the previous filter should stop sending this filter callbacks.n- **resume** provides flow control to the filter (it takes in a uint64_t as a parameter)nnReviewed By: afrindnnDifferential Revision: D17693678nnfbshipit-source-id: 4d732db47da5831bf4a3ae222216e4342d8d828fn

Allow better buffer sharing for generated H2 HEADERS framesSummary:nPrevioulsy HPACK would always allocate a buffer to hold the compressed headers (with headroom for the frame header).  Now, preallocate a block for the frame header in the writeBuf, then pass the buf directly to HPACK.  To write the frames out, we pass the contiguous header block and the writeBuf to the framer.nnThe result is that serializing many small HEADERS frames in a single loop will do fewer allocationsnnReviewed By: yairgottnnDifferential Revision: D17346736nnfbshipit-source-id: af62e39880686131d8cb936e7d1a718f8e625c7en

Replace Folly Format with fmt in logger to reduce binary sizeSummary:nNow that fmt is available in Folly builds (D14813810), use it to reduce binary code size in Folly Logger. This is done by moving most of the formatting logic behind the type-erased `vformat` API. Previously it was instantiated for all combinations of formatting argument types used in calls to `FB_LOGF` and `XLOGF` in a program.nnThe effect of this change can be illustrated by looking at symbol sizes as given by `nm -S -td` for the following test function:nn```nvoid test_log() {n  FB_LOGF(logger, WARN, num events: {:06d}, duration: {:6.3f}, 1234, 5.6789);n}n```ncompiled in `opt` mode.nn`nm` before:nn```n0000000004236736 0000000000000231 T test_log()n0000000004236992 0000000000001002 W std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > folly::LogStreamProcessor::formatLogString<int, double>(folly::Range<char const*>, int const&, double const&)n```nn`nm` after:nn```n0000000004237536 0000000000000231 T test_log()n0000000004237792 0000000000000251 W std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > folly::LogStreamProcessor::formatLogString<int, double>(folly::Range<char const*>, int const&, double const&)n0000000004238048 0000000000000740 W folly::LogStreamProcessor::vformatLogString[abi:cxx11](folly::Range<char const*>, fmt::v5::format_args, bool&)n```nnBefore we had one 1002 byte instantiation of `formatLogString<int, double>`. With this change it was reduced 4x to 251 bytes and non-template function `vformatLogString` was added which is shared among all logging calls. The size of `test_log` remained unchanged. There are even bigger savings from Folly Formatter instantiations which are no longer needed, e.g.nn```n0000000004238032 0000000000001363 W _ZNK5folly13BaseFormatterINS_9FormatterILb0EJRKiRKdEEELb0EJS3_S5_EEclIZNKS7_8appendToINSt7__cxx1112basic_stringIcSt11char_traitsIcESaIcEEEEENSt9enable_ifIXsr12IsSomeStringIT_EE5valueEvE4typeERSH_EUlNS_5RangeIPKcEEE_EEvSK_n```nnSo in total this change results in ~5x per-call/instantiation binary size. It is possible to reduce binary size even further but it is not done in the current diff to keep it manageable.nnIn addition to binary size improvements, switching to fmt will potentiallynn* allow catching errors in format strings at compile time,n* simplify future migration to C++20 [`std::format`](http://eel.is/c++draft/format).nnReviewed By: simpkinsnnDifferential Revision: D15485589nnfbshipit-source-id: 06db4436839f11c2c3dbed7b36658e2193343411n

Encode directly from HTTPMessageSummary:nThe HTTP2Codec/HPACK interface was extremely slow, as H2 had to populate a vector with the inputs expected by HPACK.  Instead, add a new HPACK API to encode an HTTPMessage directly.  This ports the logic from CodecUtil::prepareMessageForCompression.  This allows, for example, directly encoding from the HTTPHeaderCode for common headers.nnAnother design would be to change the HPACKCodec interface to have startEncode/encodeHeader/completeEncode like HPACKEncoder now has, and keep HTTPMessage out of HPACK.  I'm ok with either approach.  That actually may be slightly preferable, since it will allow the same optimization for QPACK.nnReviewed By: lnicconnDifferential Revision: D18935571nnfbshipit-source-id: acff80651a79982eb71ae398a7ed60e137d9b31fn
